[3] Diarrhea, displaced persons - Myanmar (Kachin State)
Date: Fri 30 May 2014
Source: Eleven Myanmar [edited]
http://www.elevenmyanmar.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=6303


Refugee camps in Mantwynegyi village in Mansi Township of Kachin State are suffering from an outbreak of dysentery due to over-crowding and lack of adequate hygiene. At present, there are 5 refugee camps in Mantwynegyi village and more than 6000 refugees are sheltering there, according to Zaw Latt, in charge of KPC refugee camp.

"There are about 50 patients receiving medical treatment in our relief camp every day. Among them, most of the patients are suffering from malaria and diarrhea. I think, the number of patients may have increased in June 2014. Infectious diseases are mainly due to unhygienic food and cleanliness," said nurse Nan Yaw from KPC's refugee camp.

A new refugee camp had to be extended in Mantwynegyi village to accommodate over 2000 new arrivals due to the recent fighting between the army and Kachin insurgents in April 2014. Many of the refugees worried about the education of their school-age children, let alone hygiene, food, and basic accommodation problems that come with the arrival of the monsoons.

"There are many difficulties. We face accommodation problems due to a narrow room. There are many patients increasing in the camp," said a 50-year-old woman living in KPC refugee camp.

"We worry about the education loss of our children because they are flying to our camp due to recent clashes occurred in April [2014]. There are about 200 school-aged children here," said a resident from the refugee camp.

"Currently, we don't restrict travelling in the region. But we told to the locals who are going to farm on the mountain to be careful along the main road. Last month [May 2014], most of the fighting took place in Kyar Gaun Mountain," said Lt-Col Kyaw San Oo, Battalion Commander of Light Infantry Division 83.

[Byline: Soe Tint]

